6. Thermochemical Reactions in the Atmosphere
Thermochemical reactions are driven by thermal energy (heat) rather than light. High temperatures in
combustion engines, furnaces, and lightning cause reactions that produce major atmospheric pollutants.
6.1 Thermal NOx Formation (Zeldovich Mechanism)
Thermal NOx – Extended Zeldovich Mechanism
Occurs at temperatures > 1300°C (combustion engines, power plants, lightning)
Step 1: On n 2O• (On dissociation at high T)
Step 2: O• + Nn ® NO + N• (rate-limiting step)
Step 3: N• + On ® NO + O• (chain propagation)
Step 4: N• + OH• ® NO + H• (secondary pathway)
Net: Nn + On ® 2NO (NO then oxidises to NOn)
Rate increases exponentially with T – hence "thermal" NOx
