7. Photochemical Reactions in the Atmosphere
Photochemical reactions are initiated by absorption of solar radiation (particularly UV light). A photon (hn) is
absorbed by a molecule, raising it to an excited state that then dissociates or reacts. These reactions dominate
daytime atmospheric chemistry.
7.1 Basic Photochemistry Principles
Beer–Lambert Law & Photolysis Rate
Photolysis rate constant: J = ò s(l) × f(l) × F(l) dl
where: s(l) = absorption cross-section; f(l) = quantum yield (fraction of absorptions leading to reaction);
F(l) = actinic flux (photons/cm²/s/nm)
Higher solar elevation ® larger F(l) ® faster photolysis ® more radical chemistry
