Explanation: PAN (CHnC(O)OnNOn) forms in photochemical smog from VOC oxidation + NOn. At high altitudes
and low temperatures, it is stable and acts as a reservoir, releasing NOx thousands of km away. It is also a strong
lachrymator (eye irritant) and phytotoxic at ppb concentrations.
Q6. Which compound is responsible for the catalytic destruction of stratospheric ozone and was
regulated by the Montreal Protocol?
(a) COn
(b) CHn
(c) CFCs (Chlorofluorocarbons)
(d) NnO
4 Answer: (c)
Explanation: CFCs (e.g., CFC-11 = CClnF, CFC-12 = CClnFn) are chemically inert in the troposphere but
photodissociate in the stratosphere releasing Cl•, which catalytically destroys On. The Montreal Protocol (1987)
phased out CFCs and halons.
Q7. Secondary Organic Aerosol (SOA) is formed by:
(a) Direct emission of organic particles from vehicles
(b) Oxidation of VOCs in the atmosphere followed by gas-to-particle conversion
(c) Ocean spray carrying organic compounds
(d) Volcanic emissions of organic gases
4 Answer: (b)
Explanation: SOA forms when reactive VOCs (isoprene, terpenes, benzene) are oxidised by OH•, On, or NOn• to
produce low-volatility SVOCs that condense onto pre-existing particles. SOA can make up 30–70% of PMn.n mass
in many regions.
Q8. The brown colour of photochemical smog is primarily due to:
(a) Suspended dust particles
(b) Black carbon soot
(c) NOn which absorbs blue light
(d) Ozone which absorbs visible light
4 Answer: (c)
Explanation: NOn has a characteristic brown/reddish-brown colour. It absorbs strongly at shorter wavelengths (blue),
leaving longer wavelengths (red/brown) to scatter. This gives photochemical smog its distinctive brownish haze,
especially visible in urban areas like Delhi and Los Angeles.
